comment: I am curious, what sort of story arch do all of you prefer the most personally?
honestly i find "hero saves the day" boring. So much so that if a story is only about the hero definately saving the day because he is say better than everyone else (ie superhuman) i just avoid it
I like many different stories.  Redemption, bittersweet stories, hope-against-all-odds sort of stories... especially when there's character growth
like lets take the basitin island adventure
The odd romance is good too :ctwokinds-traceflohug:
yeah sure trace helped save the basitins, but with the help and sacrifice of others so it was bittersweet so it wasnt too cliche

I simply trying to size up where my comic currently stands to what you guys are saying. I never expected this, but I have found it increasingly difficult to find a way for my protagonist, the hero, to actually do something that makes sense.
What I have come up with turns the comic, in the very end, into a strong message.
The hero wins, but not completely.
Well, I guess I have that to support my slightly unsure view.
Not all is well.  "Couldn't save everyone" sort of thing?
Don't get me wrong, the story in of itself is very interesting through and through, I am just slightly worried about the ending.
It has romance in it, loss, world building, etc.
the best way to figure out what your hero would do, vatru
is to find someone you know that thinks the same way the hero does.
Okay, so who else thinks like me?
base someone else in the shoes of your hero'
find something that would be valuable to them, even if it's not valuable to you, yourself
I do not have a plethora of individuals to chose from that could be the protagonist.
And her actions makes sense and really compares two different views on a topic.

it's just a matter of finding out what other people would do in that sort of situation rather than what you would do, and it opens up a lot of possibilities for the hero to not be so based on the creator themselves.
a lot of people base the hero on themselves, and it just turns into this kind of semi-self-insert
The end of the comic picks which view is best, so to speak. But, it is not a complete ending. Like...there is no way I can describe this without spoiling the ending.
Which I do not want to do.
Oh, yeah she is not like me. Similar but different for sure.
I just do not want the story to be so invigorating as I see it to have an ending that readers would feel to be a little flat.
I do not know, I have to work on it more and build it up.
sounds like the right thing to do
Keep at it!  Make something you're proud of

I will, it is just difficult to find a way for my protagonist to fight the antagonist in a way that makes sense to her character and my universe. This is why I said rewriting my universe is not off the table. I just feel very limited in possibilities.
I leave for five minutes for pizza bites...
That sounds good, speaking of which I am going to whip up some spaghetti.
I am going to bed as well. Goodnight everyone! :ptv-greetings:
Wasn't even a sleep. I have been working on writing my comic the entire time and it is still frustrating me! Agh!
I feel like a really good screaming would make me feel better but would not help my voice so I will settle with a Reni scream.
That aside, I have concluded that I really need to settle on a history from which my villain came from in order to determine the story. There is just too many variables without a more fixed setting.
she's... not really screaming in that image, just summoning fire from the depths
I guess either one would apply for you though.
I am calling it write now, somehow in a month or two all this will be scrapped save for the characters maybe.
you are misleading, you said you'd be going to bed. Then you didn't! What else could you bamboozle me with?
Poor phrasing on my part, I should have said I was getting off.
Here is something perplexing you that could bamboozle you, or stump you at least.
Excuse poor grammar, brain is tired from college application paragraphs.
:ptv-shock: you were right, that statement is bamboozling indeed!

So, you have a protagonist and an antagonist. The antagonist is the complex bad guy who did bad things but are they? That aside, the protagonist does not use violence or come from violence, she believes in people and lives in a world of semi-peace.
So how is she to fight and overcome said antagonist who, in his past, has used violence and was raised in a violent past?
Then please clarify because all the wires in my brain are crossed every which way.
Some in ways I do not think are possible.
"Can I get a bomb specialist in here!"
lol even if I gave you examples of bamboozlement, would you even remember?
Like I said, a lot of crossed wires, it is a fifty/fifty if the wire actually goes back to where it is suppose to, you just can't tell.
like an antagonist that actually wants peace and is non-violent, has a lot of great ideas but is surrounded by those willing to do what they are not as a means to the end.
vs a protagonist that will, objectively, go in guns blazing shoot first ask questions later, just to find out they're fighting with someone who has nothing to do with anything.
Clarification, the antagonist is the violent past one, the protagonist is the non-violent one.
no, I'm giving you a good bamboozle.
That is a pretty good bamboozle, I have to say. But, from an outside perspective, isn't the protagonist the villain, or rather, the gun-ho hero with far too many...damn...what is that word...
See, I hit a crossed wire.
Collateral, this the word. Far too much collateral damage?

But in all honesty, what I said early is the situation I find myself in with my comic right now. I just see no real way to go about solving that kind of situation. I mean, I know I said I did early but when I laid it out, it was like two/three things and
hmm, maybe not. The protag might not really be the best of guys, like uh.. that blonde dude from My Hero Academia. Rash, selfish, ignorant, severe inferiority complex, etc
but the guy's still a "hero" and still trying to stop the bad guys cuz, yknow, they're not nice.
Hmm...I get that the hero does not have to be perfect. Heck, they could just be the lesser of two evils who is fighting the greater evil and thus is the hero.
It's just, that is not the case.
I mean, this trope is one of the best I've seen, and so rarely used https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/HeroAntagonist
it's so rare to see that kinda thing put to good use
Still, that is an interesting roll but what the hell is my protagonist, or whatever roll they turn into, going to do? How will she act? That is my problem.
gotta figure it out, that's the whole thing bout writing stories
See, Christmas break is coming up.
I am going to have nothing but time on my hands.
Time to just literally go insane trying to solve this problem in my head.
And if I have to scrap everything, then what am I going to change to avoid this problem again?
I looked up and since I am wearing blue light glasses though my ceiling fan, which was out of focus, was a spider on top of my glasses.
I uh...I have nothing to say now. I am just going to be lost in thought all night.
Be sure to check that I am still sane when I turn up for streams will you Bgr?

for sake of shenanigans, what you can try to do is write a 'what if' of your story where your protag and antag's roles are reversed.. and then think about how you would tell the perspective of each one
and see if you can pull some reverse-reversals, I guess.
it's sometimes nice to just.. look at the other side of the mirror
and see if things change, or if they stay the same
and you'll never be sane as long as you're here
though the fact that you've come here proves you'll likely never be sane again.
